50|$|In declaring an <b>authority</b> or <b>body</b> an {{enforcement}} body, the Attorney-General {{must consider}} a range of factors, including whether the agency enforces the criminal law, imposes pecuniary penalties, or protects the public revenue. Subsection 176A(3B) provides that the Attorney-General must not declare an <b>authority</b> or <b>body</b> to be an ‘enforcement agency’ unless satisfied on ‘reasonable’ grounds that the <b>authority</b> or <b>body</b> has these aforementioned functions. The Attorney-General may revoke a declaration under s 176A(8) if no longer satisfied the circumstances justify the declaration remaining in force. According to the Memorandum, this section operates to ensure only <b>bodies</b> or <b>authorities</b> with a demonstrated need {{to have access to}} telecommunications data can authorise service providers to disclose information.|$|R
